China Railway, Sands China, Shimao: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-03-02T01:16:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-01/byd-great-wall-motor-pacific-basin-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  climbed 0.3 percent to 23,396.42. The
Hang Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, advanced 0.9 percent to 12,620.31.  BYD Co. (1211 HK): Shenzhen BYD Daimler New Technology Co.
Ltd., a joint venture between Daimler AG and BYD, the Chinese
carmaker part-owned by  Warren Buffett , received a business
license from the Chinese authorities, according to an e-mailed
statement. The joint venture will develop electric vehicles for
the Chinese market, the statement said. BYD shares declined 0.7
percent to HK$30.50.    Bank of China Ltd. (3988)  (3988 HK): The lender said cross-border
yuan settlement will “greatly” increase this year as
appreciation expectations make the currency more attractive.
Yuan settlement handled by domestic branches in January was 40
billion yuan ($6.1 billion), equal to a quarter of the 2010
total, Cheng Jun, general manager of global trade services for
the lender’s corporate banking unit, said at a briefing in
Beijing. The stock rose 0.2 percent to HK$4.12.    China Construction Bank Corp. (939)  (939 HK): The company will
further enhance risk management, China Securities Journal said,
citing a bank meeting in Beijing. The bank will expand further
to county-level markets and overseas, the newspaper said. The
stock gained 1 percent to HK$6.88.    China Mobile Ltd. (941)  (941 HK): China added 10.72 million
mobile phone users in January and the number of fixed-line
subscribers increased by 21,000, the Ministry of Industry and  Information Technology  said on its website. The stock increased
2.3 percent to HK$74.75.  China Railway Construction Corp. (1186 HK): The builder of
more than half the nation’s railroads said it halted work on
three construction contracts in  Libya , which have a combined
value of $4.24 billion, and has evacuated most of its workers.
The stock gained 0.7 percent to HK$8.77.  Great Wall Motor Co. (2333 HK): Tata Motors Ltd. (TTMT IN),
the Indian owner of Jaguar Land Rover, has met with companies
including Hebei-based Great Wall Motor as part of its search for
a partner to build  luxury vehicles  in China, according Carl-
Peter Forster, chief executive officer of Tata Motors. Great
Wall Motor increased 1.7 percent to HK$12.30.  Guangzhou R&F Properties Co. (2777 HK): The biggest real-
estate company in the southern Chinese city said February
contracted sales reached 1.2 billion yuan. The stock gained 3.8
percent to HK$10.84.    Pacific Basin Shipping Ltd. (2343)  (2343 HK): Hong Kong’s largest
operator of dry-bulk vessels said net income for the year ended
Dec. 31 fell to $104.3 million from $110.3 million a year
earlier. The stock jumped 5.5 percent to HK$4.78.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK): The company plans to shut its
naphtha crackers at Dushanzi plant in Xinjiang for maintenance
in August for about a month, ICIS said, citing people that it
didn’t identify. PetroChina, the nation’s biggest oil producer,
gained 0.8 percent to HK$10.68.    Sands China Ltd. (1928)  (1928 HK): The Macau unit of billionaire  Sheldon Adelson ’s casino company said 2010 net income more than
tripled to $666.5 million from $215 million. The stock increased
2.9 percent to HK$19.04.    Shimao Property Holdings Ltd. (813)  (813 HK): The developer said
it plans to sell $350 million of seven-year bonds to yield about
11 percent. The stock gained 0.2 percent to HK$10.66.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Hong Kong at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 